<br>
My only concern over that is the temperature that it would introduce into the river. As long as they did it only when the outside temp was below about 60 otherwise it would introduce warmer water into the river system.<br>
<br>
John <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#FFFFFF><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> hauloholic</span><br> <span class=usertitle>Unregistered User</span><br>   <font color=#000000>(8/14/03 7:17 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fflyfishingarkansasandmissourifrm14.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=132.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Gotcha</span><hr size=1> I guess the times of year that I find myself in Mt. Home would be the variable weather periods in general.  I don't typically come up in the middle of summer (when you'd expect it to be consistently hot and require daily generation), nor in the middle of winter (when you could expect it to be cold and require generation).  I come up for Conclave and SRG in the fall, and then Sowbug in the spring.  Might be 85 degrees one day and 35 the next...<br>
<br>
Jimmy -- why would the power company care about the oxygen levels or the fishery in general?  Are they bound by flow level regs?  We've established min flows here on the Guadalupe because the historical minimum flows (100 - 150 cfs) in the summer won't support a strong/healthy year round trout fishery.<br>
<br>
TAM <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#F9FBFD><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bflyfishingarkansasandmissouri.showUserPublicProfile?gid=flyfishar>FlyFishAR</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 448<br> <font color=#000000>(8/15/03 2:30 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fflyfishingarkansasandmissourifrm14.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=132.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.flyfishingarkansas.com/Photo%20Gallery/tn_j.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Gotcha</span><hr size=1> Troy:<br>
<br>
There is a Federal mandate that sets a minimun water quality and dissolved oxygen level to be released from the dams. However, I'm not sure what good it can do since they have no real way to &quot;introduce&quot; oxygen into the river. About all they can do is to &quot;not&quot; run water when they have low oxygen levels present in the lake. But since those levels don't change overnight they aren't likely hold water behind the dam for periods of months for the oxygen levels to correct themselves. The worst possible action they could take is to turn on 8 generators during low oxygen periods. They had a huge fish kill on the Little Red several years ago that basically caused the legislation to be introduced in the first place. However, I'm afraid it is a law without much to back itself up. <br>
<br>
Personally, I think they ought to shut the dams off during periods of questionable water quality or install some method of correcting the problem.<br>
<br>
John <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#FFFFFF><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bflyfishingarkansasandmissouri.showUserPublicProfile?gid=jimmyt@flyfishingarkansasandmissouri>Jimmy T</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 163<br> <font color=#000000>(8/16/03 11:50 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fflyfishingarkansasandmissourifrm14.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=132.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> .</span><hr size=1> Troy,<br>
<br>
John is probably right.  When they built the Dams the stocking program was part of the mitigation and keeping the fish alive is probably part of that.  Wasting water thru the Dam is not to SWPA liking because it will cost them money  They are the guys who pay for the dam!!!  so to speak.  <br>
<br>
John,<br>
This guy Mike knew about the system Rick had alluded to.  SWPA knows that fishing is big business and dosn't want to destry it.  So it sounds to me like they would spend some money to help correct the problem  IE: O'2 and temp problem but are not willing to give an extra 4 to 10 inches of water year round.  These guys like to fish too.  I also got the impression that using the min.  flow for navigation pourposes was out of the question.   <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#F9FBFD><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bflyfishingarkansasandmissouri.showUserPublicProfile?gid=jimmyt@flyfishingarkansasandmissouri>Jimmy T</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 164<br> <font color=#000000>(8/16/03 11:55 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fflyfishingarkansasandmissourifrm14.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=132.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> .</span><hr size=1> Troy,<br>
<br>
Addendum,<br>
<br>
I got the impression that they would't mind moving a little water during our really hot times by pulsing the water or giving a 1/2 generator but were not willing to do this 365 days 24/7.  <br>
<br>
Does the Guadalupe produce Power Troy???? or is it strictly for flood control???<br>
<br>
